---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidebar from '../../components/Sidebar.astro';
const title = "Particle acceleration at recollimation shocks in sub-relativistic jets - ArXiv Atlas";

import WikiLink from '../../components/WikiLink.astro';
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Particle acceleration at recollimation shocks in sub-relativistic jets</h1>

    <div class="infobox">
      <h3 class="infobox-title">Paper Details</h3>
      <table>
        <tr><th>Authors:</th><td>E. Peretti, E. Amato, S. S. Cerri, G. Morlino, L.P. Pullano, S. Recchia</td></tr>
        <tr><th>arXiv ID:</th><td><a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.16647">2603.16647</a></td></tr>
        <tr><th>Submitted:</th><td>2026-03-18</td></tr>
        <tr>
          <th>Key concepts:</th>
          <td>
            <WikiLink slug="pages/recollimation-shocks" text="Recollimation shocks" />,
            <WikiLink slug="pages/diffusive-shock-acceleration" text="DSA" />,
            <WikiLink slug="pages/jet-cocoon-systems" text="Jet-cocoon systems" />,
            <WikiLink slug="pages/astrophysical-jets" text="Astrophysical jets" />
          </td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h2 id="abstract">Abstract</h2>
    <p>Growing observational evidence suggests that sub-relativistic astrophysical jets may accelerate particles at slowly evolving standing shocks. Recollimation shocks are expected to develop when jets expand in dense environments; their formation may be mediated by the pressure of the cocoon surrounding the jet, while remaining compatible with a quasi-stationary behavior. Despite their high inclination relative to the jet axis, such shocks can be strong and enable efficient particle acceleration. This work develops a versatile modeling framework for particle acceleration via diffusive shock acceleration at recollimation shocks, applicable to Seyfert galaxies, microquasars, and protostellar systems.</p>

    <h2 id="key-findings">Key findings</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Recollimation shocks as DSA sites</strong> — Recollimation shocks in sub-relativistic jets are quasi-stationary and strong enough to be plausible sites for <WikiLink slug="pages/diffusive-shock-acceleration" text="diffusive shock acceleration" /><sup><a href="#ref-peretti">1</a></sup>.</li>
      <li><strong>Semi-analytic framework</strong> — A 1D transport model coupled to an extended <WikiLink slug="pages/Bromberg_2011" text="Bromberg et al. (2011)" /> hydrodynamic framework predicts particle spectra and maximum energies for three jet classes<sup><a href="#ref-peretti">1</a></sup>.</li>
      <li><strong>Maximum proton energies</strong> — Predicted E<sub>max</sub>: Seyferts up to PeV–EeV (depending on turbulence regime), microquasars up to tens of PeV, protostellar jets up to TeV<sup><a href="#ref-peretti">1</a></sup>.</li>
      <li><strong>Diffusion regime matters</strong> — The turbulence spectrum (Bohm, Kraichnan, or Kolmogorov) strongly shapes the cutoff energy and spectral form; Bohm gives highest E<sub>max</sub>, Kolmogorov the lowest<sup><a href="#ref-peretti">1</a></sup>.</li>
      <li><strong>Upstream confinement</strong> — Upstream diffusion length relative to shock position typically sets E<sub>max</sub>, though downstream turbulence decay can become the limiting factor<sup><a href="#ref-peretti">1</a></sup>.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="method">Method</h2>
    <p>The authors extend the analytic jet–cocoon formalism of <WikiLink slug="pages/Bromberg_2011" text="Bromberg et al. (2011)" /> to the sub-relativistic regime, deriving cocoon pressure P<sub>c</sub>(t), jet-head position z<sub>h</sub>(t), and <WikiLink slug="pages/recollimation-shocks" text="recollimation-shock" /> height. Self-similar scalings (analogous to <a href="https://doi.org/10.1086/155692">Weaver 1977</a> wind-blown bubbles) yield P<sub>c</sub> ~ t<sup>-4/5</sup>. Oblique shock jump conditions are parameterized via k<sub>p</sub>, and a semi-analytic 1D spatially-dependent transport equation is solved iteratively to obtain particle spectra at the shock<sup><a href="#ref-peretti">1</a>, <a href="#ref-bromberg">2</a></sup>.</p>

    <h2 id="results">Results by source class</h2>
    <h3>Seyfert jets (SEY<sub>0</sub>)</h3>
    <p>Using NGC 4151–inspired parameters, the model predicts proton acceleration up to PeV–EeV energies under Bohm diffusion, with Kraichnan as a realistic benchmark yielding E<sub>max</sub> ~ 10<sup>17</sup>–10<sup>18</sup> eV<sup><a href="#ref-peretti">1</a>, <a href="#ref-ulvestad">3</a></sup>.</p>

    <h3>Microquasar jets (MQ<sub>0</sub>)</h3>
    <p>SS433-inspired prototype parameters yield E<sub>max</sub> up to tens of PeV, consistent with recent HAWC and H.E.S.S. detections of TeV emission from SS433<sup><a href="#ref-peretti">1</a>, <a href="#ref-hawc">4</a>, <a href="#ref-hess">5</a></sup>.</p>

    <h3>Protostellar jets (PS<sub>0</sub>)</h3>
    <p>HH80-81–based parameters predict proton energies reaching TeV under Kraichnan diffusion, with Kolmogorov yielding only GeV-scale acceleration<sup><a href="#ref-peretti">1</a>, <a href="#ref-rodriguez">6</a></sup>.</p>

    <h2 id="significance">Significance</h2>
    <p>This paper provides the first unified semi-analytic framework for DSA at recollimation shocks across three classes of sub-relativistic jets. It demonstrates that recollimation shocks — previously understudied as particle accelerators — can be highly efficient, with implications for PeVatron candidates among microquasars and Seyferts. The work also highlights that escaped protons may produce extended hadronic emission from <WikiLink slug="pages/jet-cocoon-systems" text="jet cocoons" />, connecting to multi-messenger predictions.</p>

    <h2 id="limitations">Limitations &amp; future work</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>1D model omits multi-dimensional transport effects and lateral escape</li>
      <li>Oblique-shock physics (guide-field effects, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1086/166490">Kirk 1989</a>) not fully captured</li>
      <li>Sub-relativistic only; relativistic generalization needed for fast AGN jets</li>
      <li>Microphysics at jet head and downstream turbulence decay remain uncertain</li>
    </ul>

